---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Timeline from '../components/Timeline.astro';
import { href } from '../utils';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="History of Technology in SPPS"
  description="An interactive timeline of technology in Saint Paul Public Schools classrooms — from the 2012 referendum and the 1:1 iPad rollout to today's device policies."
>
  <h1>History of Technology in SPPS</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    How did a screen end up on every desk in Saint Paul? Filter the timeline by
    category to follow the money, the devices, or the policy. Every entry is
    sourced.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>Kept current automatically.</strong> This site monitors the SPPS
      board policy pages and Minnesota statutes for changes every week. When the
      district or the Legislature changes the rules, the timeline gets updated —
      see <a href={href('/policy/')}>Current Policy</a> for the latest.
    </p>
  </div>

  <Timeline />

  <h2>What the timeline shows</h2>
  <p>
    Three things stand out. First, the devices arrived through a funding pivot,
    not a pedagogical plan: voters approved a technology levy in 2012 after being
    told it would not fund a device for every student — and within two years it
    was funding exactly that. Second, for roughly a decade there was no
    districtwide policy governing the technology in students' hands; the rules
    that exist today arrived only after the state required them in 2024. Third,
    the policy SPPS adopted covers students' personal phones — it does not
    address the district's own devices, the apps on them, or screen time during
    instruction. The history suggests a question worth asking at any board
    meeting: when did the district last evaluate whether its 1:1 program improves
    learning?
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
